nts -- tThe Movement Takes the Lead: The Role of Lawyers in the Struggle for a Living Wage in Santa Monica, California -- tA Movement in the Wake of a New Law: The United Farm Workers and the California Agricultural Lab or Relations Act -- tMobilization Lawyering: Community Economic Development in the Figueroa Corridor -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCause Lawyers and Social Movements seeks to reorient scholarship on cause lawyers, inviting scholars to think about cause lawyering from the perspective of those political activists with whom cause lawyers work and whom they seek to serve. It demonstrates that while all cause lawyering cuts against the grain of conventional understandings of legal practice and professionalism, social movement lawyering poses distinctively thorny problems. The editors and authors of this volume explore the following questions: What do cause lawyers do for, and to, social movements? How, when, and why do social movements turn to and use lawyers and legal strategies? Does their use of lawyers and legal strategies advance or constrain the achievement of their goals? And, how do movements shape the lawyers who serve them and how do lawyers shape the movements?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCause lawyerszUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 4aLaw -- Jurisprudence. 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 4aPolitics -- Democracy and Human Rights. 7aLAW / Legal Profession.2bisacsh1 aBarclay, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBibler Coutin, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Scott L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDen Dulk, Kevin R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g